     230                 :            : 
     231                 :            : /* Define the register numbers to be used in Dwarf debugging information.
     232                 :            :    The SVR4 reference port C compiler uses the following register numbers
     233                 :            :    in its Dwarf output code:
     234                 :            :         0 for %eax (gcc regno = 0)
     235                 :            :         1 for %ecx (gcc regno = 2)
     236                 :            :         2 for %edx (gcc regno = 1)
     237                 :            :         3 for %ebx (gcc regno = 3)
     238                 :            :         4 for %esp (gcc regno = 7)
     239                 :            :         5 for %ebp (gcc regno = 6)
     240                 :            :         6 for %esi (gcc regno = 4)
     241                 :            :         7 for %edi (gcc regno = 5)
     242                 :            :    The following three DWARF register numbers are never generated by
     243                 :            :    the SVR4 C compiler or by the GNU compilers, but SDB on x86/svr4
     244                 :            :    believed these numbers have these meanings.
     245                 :            :         8  for %eip    (no gcc equivalent)
     246                 :            :         9  for %eflags (gcc regno = 17)
     247                 :            :         10 for %trapno (no gcc equivalent)
     248                 :            :    It is not at all clear how we should number the FP stack registers
     249                 :            :    for the x86 architecture.  If the version of SDB on x86/svr4 were
     250                 :            :    a bit less brain dead with respect to floating-point then we would
     251                 :            :    have a precedent to follow with respect to DWARF register numbers
     252                 :            :    for x86 FP registers, but the SDB on x86/svr4 was so completely
     253                 :            :    broken with respect to FP registers that it is hardly worth thinking
     254                 :            :    of it as something to strive for compatibility with.
     255                 :            :    The version of x86/svr4 SDB I had does (partially)
     256                 :            :    seem to believe that DWARF register number 11 is associated with
     257                 :            :    the x86 register %st(0), but that's about all.  Higher DWARF
     258                 :            :    register numbers don't seem to be associated with anything in
     259                 :            :    particular, and even for DWARF regno 11, SDB only seemed to under-
     260                 :            :    stand that it should say that a variable lives in %st(0) (when
     261                 :            :    asked via an `=' command) if we said it was in DWARF regno 11,
     262                 :            :    but SDB still printed garbage when asked for the value of the
     263                 :            :    variable in question (via a `/' command).
     264                 :            :    (Also note that the labels SDB printed for various FP stack regs
     265                 :            :    when doing an `x' command were all wrong.)
     266                 :            :    Note that these problems generally don't affect the native SVR4
     267                 :            :    C compiler because it doesn't allow the use of -O with -g and
     268                 :            :    because when it is *not* optimizing, it allocates a memory
     269                 :            :    location for each floating-point variable, and the memory
     270                 :            :    location is what gets described in the DWARF AT_location
     271                 :            :    attribute for the variable in question.
     272                 :            :    Regardless of the severe mental illness of the x86/svr4 SDB, we
     273                 :            :    do something sensible here and we use the following DWARF
     274                 :            :    register numbers.  Note that these are all stack-top-relative
     275                 :            :    numbers.
     276                 :            :         11 for %st(0) (gcc regno = 8)
     277                 :            :         12 for %st(1) (gcc regno = 9)
     278                 :            :         13 for %st(2) (gcc regno = 10)
     279                 :            :         14 for %st(3) (gcc regno = 11)
     280                 :            :         15 for %st(4) (gcc regno = 12)
     281                 :            :         16 for %st(5) (gcc regno = 13)
     282                 :            :         17 for %st(6) (gcc regno = 14)
     283                 :            :         18 for %st(7) (gcc regno = 15)
     284                 :            : */

   12548                 :            : /* Print the name of register X to FILE based on its machine mode and number.
   12549                 :            :    If CODE is 'w', pretend the mode is HImode.
   12550                 :            :    If CODE is 'b', pretend the mode is QImode.
   12551                 :            :    If CODE is 'k', pretend the mode is SImode.
   12552                 :            :    If CODE is 'q', pretend the mode is DImode.
   12553                 :            :    If CODE is 'x', pretend the mode is V4SFmode.
   12554                 :            :    If CODE is 't', pretend the mode is V8SFmode.

   12713                 :            : /* Meaning of CODE:
   12714                 :            :    L,W,B,Q,S,T -- print the opcode suffix for specified size of operand.
   12715                 :            :    C -- print opcode suffix for set/cmov insn.
   12716                 :            :    c -- like C, but print reversed condition
   12717                 :            :    F,f -- likewise, but for floating-point.
   12718                 :            :    O -- if HAVE_AS_IX86_CMOV_SUN_SYNTAX, expand to "w.", "l." or "q.",
   12719                 :            :         otherwise nothing
   12720                 :            :    R -- print embedded rounding and sae.
   12721                 :            :    r -- print only sae.
   12722                 :            :    z -- print the opcode suffix for the size of the current operand.
   12723                 :            :    Z -- likewise, with special suffixes for x87 instructions.
   12724                 :            :    * -- print a star (in certain assembler syntax)
   12725                 :            :    A -- print an absolute memory reference.
   12726                 :            :    E -- print address with DImode register names if TARGET_64BIT.
   12727                 :            :    w -- print the operand as if it's a "word" (HImode) even if it isn't.
   12728                 :            :    s -- print a shift double count, followed by the assemblers argument
   12729                 :            :         delimiter.
   12730                 :            :    b -- print the QImode name of the register for the indicated operand.
   12731                 :            :         %b0 would print %al if operands[0] is reg 0.
   12732                 :            :    w --  likewise, print the HImode name of the register.
   12733                 :            :    k --  likewise, print the SImode name of the register.
   12734                 :            :    q --  likewise, print the DImode name of the register.
   12735                 :            :    x --  likewise, print the V4SFmode name of the register.
   12736                 :            :    t --  likewise, print the V8SFmode name of the register.
   12737                 :            :    g --  likewise, print the V16SFmode name of the register.
   12738                 :            :    h -- print the QImode name for a "high" register, either ah, bh, ch or dh.
   12739                 :            :    y -- print "st(0)" instead of "st" as a register.
   12740                 :            :    d -- print duplicated register operand for AVX instruction.
   12741                 :            :    D -- print condition for SSE cmp instruction.
   12742                 :            :    P -- if PIC, print an @PLT suffix.  For -fno-plt, load function
   12743                 :            :         address from GOT.
   12744                 :            :    p -- print raw symbol name.
   12745                 :            :    X -- don't print any sort of PIC '@' suffix for a symbol.
   12746                 :            :    & -- print some in-use local-dynamic symbol name.
   12747                 :            :    H -- print a memory address offset by 8; used for sse high-parts
   12748                 :            :    Y -- print condition for XOP pcom* instruction.
   12749                 :            :    V -- print naked full integer register name without %.
   12750                 :            :    + -- print a branch hint as 'cs' or 'ds' prefix
   12751                 :            :    ; -- print a semicolon (after prefixes due to bug in older gas).
   12752                 :            :    ~ -- print "i" if TARGET_AVX2, "f" otherwise.
   12753                 :            :    ^ -- print addr32 prefix if TARGET_64BIT and Pmode != word_mode
   12754                 :            :    M -- print addr32 prefix for TARGET_X32 with VSIB address.
   12755                 :            :    ! -- print NOTRACK prefix for jxx/call/ret instructions if required.
   12756                 :            :    N -- print maskz if it's constant 0 operand.
   12757                 :            :  */
   12758                 :            :

   22991                 :            : /* Address space support.
   22992                 :            : 
   22993                 :            :    This is not "far pointers" in the 16-bit sense, but an easy way
   22994                 :            :    to use %fs and %gs segment prefixes.  Therefore:
   22995                 :            : 
   22996                 :            :     (a) All address spaces have the same modes,
   22997                 :            :     (b) All address spaces have the same addresss forms,
   22998                 :            :     (c) While %fs and %gs are technically subsets of the generic
   22999                 :            :         address space, they are probably not subsets of each other.
   23000                 :            :     (d) Since we have no access to the segment base register values
   23001                 :            :         without resorting to a system call, we cannot convert a
   23002                 :            :         non-default address space to a default address space.
   23003                 :            :         Therefore we do not claim %fs or %gs are subsets of generic.
   23004                 :            : 
   23005                 :            :    Therefore we can (mostly) use the default hooks.  */

   23157                 :            :       ASSERT_EQ (SImode, GET_MODE (dest));
   23158                 :            :       {
   23159                 :            :         rtx addr = XEXP (dest, 0);
   23160                 :            :         ASSERT_EQ (PLUS, GET_CODE (addr));
   23161                 :            :         ASSERT_EQ (DImode, GET_MODE (addr));
   23162                 :            :         {
   23163                 :            :           rtx lhs = XEXP (addr, 0);
   23164                 :            :           /* Verify that the "frame" REG was consolidated.  */
   23165                 :            :           ASSERT_RTX_PTR_EQ (frame_pointer_rtx, lhs);
   23166                 :            :         }
   23167                 :            :         {
   23168                 :            :           rtx rhs = XEXP (addr, 1);
   23169                 :            :           ASSERT_EQ (CONST_INT, GET_CODE (rhs));
   23170                 :            :           ASSERT_EQ (-4, INTVAL (rhs));
   23171                 :            :         }
   23172                 :            :       }
   23173                 :            :       /* Verify the "[1 i+0 S4 A32]" was parsed.  */
   23174                 :            :       ASSERT_EQ (1, MEM_ALIAS_SET (dest));
   23175                 :            :       /* "i" should have been handled by synthesizing a global int
   23176                 :            :          variable named "i".  */
   23177                 :            :       mem_expr = MEM_EXPR (dest);
   23178                 :            :       ASSERT_NE (mem_expr, NULL);
   23179                 :            :       ASSERT_EQ (VAR_DECL, TREE_CODE (mem_expr));
   23180                 :            :       ASSERT_EQ (integer_type_node, TREE_TYPE (mem_expr));
   23181                 :            :       ASSERT_EQ (IDENTIFIER_NODE, TREE_CODE (DECL_NAME (mem_expr)));
   23182                 :            :       ASSERT_STREQ ("i", IDENTIFIER_POINTER (DECL_NAME (mem_expr)));
   23183                 :            :       /* "+0".  */
   23184                 :            :       ASSERT_TRUE (MEM_OFFSET_KNOWN_P (dest));
   23185                 :            :       ASSERT_EQ (0, MEM_OFFSET (dest));
   23186                 :            :       /* "S4".  */
   23187                 :            :       ASSERT_EQ (4, MEM_SIZE (dest));
   23188                 :            :       /* "A32.  */
   23189                 :            :       ASSERT_EQ (32, MEM_ALIGN (dest));
   23190                 :            :     }
   23191                 :            :     {
   23192                 :            :       rtx src = SET_SRC (pat);
   23193                 :            :       ASSERT_EQ (REG, GET_CODE (src));
   23194                 :            :       ASSERT_EQ (SImode, GET_MODE (src));
   23195                 :            :       ASSERT_EQ (5, REGNO (src));
   23196                 :            :       tree reg_expr = REG_EXPR (src);
   23197                 :            :       /* "i" here should point to the same var as for the MEM_EXPR.  */
   23198                 :            :       ASSERT_EQ (reg_expr, mem_expr);
   23199                 :            :     }
   23200                 :            :   }
   23201                 :            : }
   23202                 :            : 
   23203                 :            : /* Verify that the RTL loader copes with a call_insn dump.
   23204                 :            :    This test is target-specific since the dump contains a target-specific
   23205                 :            :    hard reg name.  */
   23206                 :            : 
   23207                 :            : static void
   23208                 :            : ix86_test_loading_call_insn ()
   23209                 :            : {
   23210                 :            :   /* The test dump includes register "xmm0", where requires TARGET_SSE
   23211                 :            :      to exist.  */
   23212                 :            :   if (!TARGET_SSE)
   23213                 :            :     return;
   23214                 :            : 
   23215                 :            :   rtl_dump_test t (SELFTEST_LOCATION, locate_file ("x86_64/call-insn.rtl"));
   23216                 :            : 
   23217                 :            :   rtx_insn *insn = get_insns ();
   23218                 :            :   ASSERT_EQ (CALL_INSN, GET_CODE (insn));
   23219                 :            : 
   23220                 :            :   /* "/j".  */
   23221                 :            :   ASSERT_TRUE (RTX_FLAG (insn, jump));
   23222                 :            : 
   23223                 :            :   rtx pat = PATTERN (insn);
   23224                 :            :   ASSERT_EQ (CALL, GET_CODE (SET_SRC (pat)));
   23225                 :            : 
   23226                 :            :   /* Verify REG_NOTES.  */
   23227                 :            :   {
   23228                 :            :     /* "(expr_list:REG_CALL_DECL".   */
   23229                 :            :     ASSERT_EQ (EXPR_LIST, GET_CODE (REG_NOTES (insn)));
   23230                 :            :     rtx_expr_list *note0 = as_a <rtx_expr_list *> (REG_NOTES (insn));
   23231                 :            :     ASSERT_EQ (REG_CALL_DECL, REG_NOTE_KIND (note0));
   23232                 :            : 
   23233                 :            :     /* "(expr_list:REG_EH_REGION (const_int 0 [0])".  */
   23234                 :            :     rtx_expr_list *note1 = note0->next ();
   23235                 :            :     ASSERT_EQ (REG_EH_REGION, REG_NOTE_KIND (note1));
   23236                 :            : 
   23237                 :            :     ASSERT_EQ (NULL, note1->next ());
   23238                 :            :   }
   23239                 :            : 
   23240                 :            :   /* Verify CALL_INSN_FUNCTION_USAGE.  */
   23241                 :            :   {
   23242                 :            :     /* "(expr_list:DF (use (reg:DF 21 xmm0))".  */
   23243                 :            :     rtx_expr_list *usage
   23244                 :            :       = as_a <rtx_expr_list *> (CALL_INSN_FUNCTION_USAGE (insn));
   23245                 :            :     ASSERT_EQ (EXPR_LIST, GET_CODE (usage));
   23246                 :            :     ASSERT_EQ (DFmode, GET_MODE (usage));
   23247                 :            :     ASSERT_EQ (USE, GET_CODE (usage->element ()));
   23248                 :            :     ASSERT_EQ (NULL, usage->next ());
   23249                 :            :   }
   23250                 :            : }
   23251                 :            : 
   23252                 :            : /* Verify that the RTL loader copes a dump from print_rtx_function.
   23253                 :            :    This test is target-specific since the dump contains target-specific
   23254                 :            :    hard reg names.  */
   23255                 :            : 
   23256                 :            : static void
   23257                 :            : ix86_test_loading_full_dump ()
   23258                 :            : {
   23259                 :            :   rtl_dump_test t (SELFTEST_LOCATION, locate_file ("x86_64/times-two.rtl"));
   23260                 :            : 
   23261                 :            :   ASSERT_STREQ ("times_two", IDENTIFIER_POINTER (DECL_NAME (cfun->decl)));
   23262                 :            : 
   23263                 :            :   rtx_insn *insn_1 = get_insn_by_uid (1);
   23264                 :            :   ASSERT_EQ (NOTE, GET_CODE (insn_1));
   23265                 :            : 
   23266                 :            :   rtx_insn *insn_7 = get_insn_by_uid (7);
   23267                 :            :   ASSERT_EQ (INSN, GET_CODE (insn_7));
   23268                 :            :   ASSERT_EQ (PARALLEL, GET_CODE (PATTERN (insn_7)));
   23269                 :            :

   23271                 :            :   ASSERT_EQ (INSN, GET_CODE (insn_15));
   23272                 :            :   ASSERT_EQ (USE, GET_CODE (PATTERN (insn_15)));
   23273                 :            :

   23276                 :            :   ASSERT_EQ (0, REGNO (crtl->return_rtx));
   23277                 :            :   ASSERT_EQ (SImode, GET_MODE (crtl->return_rtx));
   23278                 :            : }
   23279                 :            : 
   23280                 :            : /* Verify that the RTL loader copes with UNSPEC and UNSPEC_VOLATILE insns.
   23281                 :            :    In particular, verify that it correctly loads the 2nd operand.
   23282                 :            :    This test is target-specific since these are machine-specific
   23283                 :            :    operands (and enums).  */
   23284                 :            : 
   23285                 :            : static void
   23286                 :            : ix86_test_loading_unspec ()
   23287                 :            : {
   23288                 :            :   rtl_dump_test t (SELFTEST_LOCATION, locate_file ("x86_64/unspec.rtl"));
   23289                 :            : 
   23290                 :            :   ASSERT_STREQ ("test_unspec", IDENTIFIER_POINTER (DECL_NAME (cfun->decl)));
   23291                 :            : 
   23292                 :            :   ASSERT_TRUE (cfun);
   23293                 :            : 
   23294                 :            :   /* Test of an UNSPEC.  */
   23295                 :            :    rtx_insn *insn = get_insns ();
   23296                 :            :   ASSERT_EQ (INSN, GET_CODE (insn));
   23297                 :            :   rtx set = single_set (insn);
   23298                 :            :   ASSERT_NE (NULL, set);
   23299                 :            :   rtx dst = SET_DEST (set);
   23300                 :            :   ASSERT_EQ (MEM, GET_CODE (dst));
   23301                 :            :   rtx src = SET_SRC (set);
   23302                 :            :   ASSERT_EQ (UNSPEC, GET_CODE (src));
   23303                 :            :   ASSERT_EQ (BLKmode, GET_MODE (src));
   23304                 :            :   ASSERT_EQ (UNSPEC_MEMORY_BLOCKAGE, XINT (src, 1));
   23305                 :            : 
   23306                 :            :   rtx v0 = XVECEXP (src, 0, 0);
   23307                 :            : 
   23308                 :            :   /* Verify that the two uses of the first SCRATCH have pointer
   23309                 :            :      equality.  */
   23310                 :            :   rtx scratch_a = XEXP (dst, 0);
   23311                 :            :   ASSERT_EQ (SCRATCH, GET_CODE (scratch_a));
   23312                 :            : 
   23313                 :            :   rtx scratch_b = XEXP (v0, 0);
   23314                 :            :   ASSERT_EQ (SCRATCH, GET_CODE (scratch_b));
   23315                 :            : 
   23316                 :            :   ASSERT_EQ (scratch_a, scratch_b);
   23317                 :            : 
   23318                 :            :   /* Verify that the two mems are thus treated as equal.  */
   23319                 :            :   ASSERT_TRUE (rtx_equal_p (dst, v0));
   23320                 :            : 
   23321                 :            :   /* Verify that the insn is recognized.  */
   23322                 :            :   ASSERT_NE(-1, recog_memoized (insn));
   23323                 :            : 
   23324                 :            :   /* Test of an UNSPEC_VOLATILE, which has its own enum values.  */
   23325                 :            :   insn = NEXT_INSN (insn);
   23326                 :            :   ASSERT_EQ (INSN, GET_CODE (insn));
   23327                 :            : 
   23328                 :            :   set = single_set (insn);
   23329                 :            :   ASSERT_NE (NULL, set);
   23330                 :            : 
   23331                 :            :   src = SET_SRC (set);
   23332                 :            :   ASSERT_EQ (UNSPEC_VOLATILE, GET_CODE (src));
   23333                 :            :   ASSERT_EQ (UNSPECV_RDTSCP, XINT (src, 1));
   23334                 :            : }
